// ============================== 6. SELECTION ===============================
children.push(
  h1("6. Justification for the Selected Model"),
  h2("6.1 The selection rule, fixed in code before any test result existed"),
  p("The rule below was written into src/train.py as executable code before the test set was scored. This is what makes the held-out evaluation unbiased: a rule chosen after seeing test numbers is not a rule."),
  code([
    "1. Compare candidates by mean ROC-AUC under stratified 5-fold",
    "   cross-validation on the TRAINING SPLIT ONLY.",
    "2. If the two means differ by less than 0.01, break the tie on mean CV F1.",
    "3. If that gap is also under 0.01, break the tie on mean CV recall,",
    "   because a missed churner costs more than an unnecessary review.",
    "4. Score the held-out test set ONCE, after selection, for reporting only.",
  ]),
  h2("6.2 What the rule actually did"),
  p("The two candidates were effectively tied. Cross-validated ROC-AUC differed by 0.0005 (0.8460 against 0.8454) and F1 by 0.0010 (0.6286 against 0.6296). Both gaps fell inside the 0.01 tolerance, so the rule fell through to cross-validated recall, where Logistic Regression led 0.8013 to 0.7632."),
  p([{ t: "Logistic Regression was therefore selected.", b: true }]),
  h2("6.3 An honest note for examination"),
  callout(
    "Stated openly rather than omitted.",
    "On the held-out test set the Random Forest is marginally better on accuracy (0.7608 against 0.7374), precision (0.5337 against 0.5034) and F1 (0.6349 against 0.6130), with identical recall (0.7834) and effectively identical ROC-AUC (0.8417 against 0.8414). The model was not switched. Reselecting after seeing test results would convert the held-out set into a selection set and invalidate every unbiasedness claim in this report. The two models are close enough that either is defensible; what is not defensible is choosing after peeking.",
    "B45309"
  ),
  h2("6.4 Supporting reasons for the linear model"),
  bullet("Its coefficients yield an exact per-prediction contribution decomposition, used in Section 7.4. No approximation is required."),
  bullet("It produces a smaller artifact (8.4 KB) and faster inference, which matters for a container that must start quickly."),
  bullet("It is far easier to defend to a model-risk reviewer than an ensemble of 400 trees."),
  h2("6.5 Saved artifact and reproducibility"),
  table(
    ["Artifact", "Contents"],
    [
      ["model_pipeline.joblib", "The complete pipeline — preprocessing and estimator together, 8.4 KB"],
      ["model_metadata.json", "Model name, version, training timestamp, seed, dataset blob SHA, metrics, confusion matrix, environment versions"],
      ["feature_schema.json", "Predictors, dtypes, observed training categories, numeric bounds, target mapping, UI labels and grouping"],
      ["reference_rates.json", "Descriptive statistics used only for the application's context charts"],
      ["model_card.md", "Intended use, out-of-scope uses, provenance, metrics, limitations, ethics, human-review requirement"],
    ],
    [28, 72]
  ),
  spacer(),
  p([
    { t: "Saving the whole pipeline rather than the estimator alone means the deployed transformation cannot differ from the trained one. The artifact is 8.4 KB, so " },
    { t: "Git LFS is not required", b: true },
    { t: " — this was measured, not assumed. Reproducibility is guaranteed by a fixed seed, pinned dependency versions and the verified dataset SHA; retraining produces byte-identical metrics." },
  ]),
  pageBreak()
);

